    term: "Deep Learning",
    slug: "deep-learning",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Deep learning is a subfield of machine learning that builds computational models inspired by the structure and function of the human brain. These models, called neural networks, consist of many layers of interconnected artificial neurons that transform input data into increasingly abstract representations. By stacking layers, the system can learn to recognize patterns directly from raw data such as images, sound, or text, without needing hand-crafted features. The term \"deep\" refers to the number of layers; modern implementations often contain dozens or even hundreds of them.\n\nA helpful way to picture deep learning is to compare it with a team of chefs preparing a complex dish. The first chef receives raw ingredients and performs basic cuts, the next chef adds seasoning, the following one cooks, and the final chef plates the meal. Each chef's work depends on the output of the previous one, and the quality of the final dish improves as the team refines each step. In a neural network, each layer acts like a chef, applying a simple mathematical operation to the data it receives, then passing the result forward. Through repeated exposure to examples, the network adjusts the way each layer works, gradually producing a more accurate output.\n\nThe practical impact of deep learning is evident in many everyday technologies. Speech-recognition systems translate spoken words into text, image-search engines label pictures, and recommendation engines suggest videos or products based on subtle user preferences. These applications succeed because deep networks can capture intricate relationships that traditional algorithms miss, allowing computers to perform tasks that once required human intuition.\n\nBeyond consumer products, deep learning drives progress in fields that affect public health, safety, and the environment. Medical imaging tools can highlight tumors with higher precision, autonomous vehicles interpret road conditions in real time, and climate models analyze massive satellite datasets to improve forecasting. As hardware becomes faster and data collections grow, deep learning will continue to expand the range of problems that machines can solve, making it a central technology for future innovation.",
