    term: "Transformer Architecture",
    slug: "transformer-architecture",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "The Transformer architecture is a neural-network design that processes sequences of data - such as words in a sentence or frames in a video - without relying on recurrent connections. First introduced in 2017, it replaces the older step-by-step processing style with a structure built around attention mechanisms, which let every element of the input consider every other element at once. The model consists of an encoder stack that turns raw inputs into rich representations and a decoder stack that turns those representations back into a target sequence. Because the same building blocks repeat across layers, the design scales well to very large models.  \n\nImagine a group of people sitting around a table, each holding a piece of a puzzle. In a traditional recurrent system, one person would whisper their piece to the next, and the message would travel around the table many times before everyone understands the whole picture. In a Transformer, every person can look directly at all other pieces at the same time, deciding which ones are most relevant for their own part of the puzzle. This simultaneous \"look-around\" step is called self-attention, and it lets the network combine information quickly and without the bottleneck of a single pass.  \n\nBecause it can handle long-range dependencies efficiently, the Transformer has become the backbone of most modern language-understanding systems. It powers translation services that convert text between dozens of languages with human-like fluency, fuels chat assistants that generate coherent replies, and drives search engines that rank results based on contextual meaning rather than keyword matching. The same attention-driven design also works for images, where it replaces convolutional layers to capture relationships between distant pixels, and for protein-folding tasks, where it learns patterns across thousands of amino-acid positions.  \n\nCompanies adopt Transformers because the same model can be fine-tuned for many downstream tasks, saving time and compute compared with training separate architectures from scratch. As hardware improves, researchers build larger stacks with billions of parameters, achieving performance that surpasses earlier benchmarks on reading comprehension, code generation, and even scientific discovery. The ability to learn directly from raw data without handcrafted features means the architecture continues to open new applications, from personalized recommendation engines to real-time video captioning, making it a central tool in today's AI ecosystem.",
