    term: "AI Alignment",
    slug: "ai-alignment",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "AI alignment is the field of research and engineering that tries to make artificial intelligence systems pursue goals that match the intentions, values, and safety requirements of the people who create or use them. It treats an AI model as a tool whose behavior can be shaped, and it asks how to specify, verify, and enforce that the tool does not act in ways that are harmful, unexpected, or contrary to human preferences. The problem becomes harder as systems grow more capable, because a powerful AI can find shortcuts or interpret instructions in ways that were not anticipated by its designers.\n\nA useful way to picture alignment is to think of a thermostat in a house. You set the thermostat to keep the temperature at a comfortable level. The thermostat's job is simple: read the current temperature, compare it to the target, and turn the heater or air conditioner on or off to stay close to that target. If the thermostat is poorly calibrated, it might overheat the house or freeze it, despite the user's wishes. Similarly, an aligned AI must continuously read its environment, compare its actions to the intended goal, and adjust its output so that the result stays within the acceptable range.\n\nToday, AI systems already influence hiring decisions, medical diagnoses, financial trading, and content recommendation. When these systems act on incomplete data or hidden biases, the outcomes can reinforce discrimination, spread misinformation, or cause economic loss. Alignment research provides methods to detect such failures early, to embed fairness constraints, and to create fail-safe mechanisms that stop an AI from pursuing a path that could damage users or society. Without these safeguards, the rapid deployment of powerful models could outpace the ability of regulators and the public to respond.\n\nGovernments and corporations are beginning to draft standards that require AI products to meet alignment criteria before they reach customers. Researchers are building verification tools that treat an AI's code like a contract, checking that it cannot break agreed-upon rules even in novel situations. As AI becomes more autonomous - driving cars, managing energy grids, or negotiating contracts - alignment will determine whether these technologies amplify human well-being or generate new sources of risk. Investing in alignment today reduces the chance of costly corrections later.",
