    term: "AI Safety",
    slug: "ai-safety",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "AI safety is the discipline that studies how to design, build, test, and operate artificial intelligence systems so that they behave in ways that align with human intentions and do not cause unintended harm. It covers everything from low-level bugs in a self-driving car's perception pipeline to high-level questions about how a powerful language model might influence public opinion. Practitioners combine insights from computer science, engineering, cognitive psychology, and ethics to create guidelines, verification methods, and control mechanisms that keep AI outputs trustworthy and predictable.\n\nThink of AI safety like the safety features in a modern car. When you sit behind the wheel, you trust the brakes, airbags, and electronic stability control to react correctly if something goes wrong. Engineers test those systems under many conditions, add redundant sensors, and program limits that stop the car from exceeding safe speeds. In the same way, AI safety adds monitoring tools, fallback procedures, and alignment checks that intervene when an algorithm starts to drift away from its intended goal. The analogy highlights that safety is not a single gadget but a layered set of protections built into the whole vehicle.\n\nToday, AI systems are moving from research labs into everyday products such as medical diagnosis tools, financial trading bots, and content recommendation engines. When those systems make mistakes, the consequences can range from a misdiagnosed disease to a market flash crash or the spread of harmful misinformation. Without strong safety practices, a single error can cascade through interconnected services and affect millions of users. Governments, corporations, and civil society are already investing in standards, audits, and certification programs to keep these technologies in check. The goal is to ensure that progress in capability does not outpace our ability to control risk.\n\nLooking ahead, increasingly autonomous systems could make decisions that shape infrastructure, climate policy, or even legal judgments. If those decisions are not aligned with shared human values, the damage could be irreversible. Researchers therefore explore formal verification, incentive design, and interpretability techniques that aim to guarantee safe behavior even as AI grows more capable. Building these safeguards now helps avoid a future where unchecked intelligence becomes a source of systemic risk.",
