    term: "Support Vector Machine (SVM)",
    slug: "support-vector-machine-svm",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a supervised learning algorithm used for classification and regression tasks. It builds a model that separates data points into distinct categories by finding the optimal hyperplane - a flat decision surface - in a multidimensional feature space. The hyperplane is chosen so that the margin, the distance between the closest points of each class and the plane, is maximized. The closest points are called support vectors because they \"support\" the position of the hyperplane. By focusing on the most informative examples, SVM can achieve high accuracy even when the number of features exceeds the number of samples.  \n\nImagine a table with two types of magnets scattered on it, and you need to place an invisible sheet that separates the types without touching any magnet. You slide the sheet until it is as far as possible from the nearest magnet on each side; the magnets that touch the sheet define its position. In SVM terms, the sheet is the hyperplane, the distance to the nearest magnets is the margin, and the touching magnets are the support vectors. If a flat sheet cannot separate the magnets, the algorithm lifts the data into a higher-dimensional space where a curved surface becomes flat, finds the separating plane there, and projects the result back.  \n\nThe practical value of SVM lies in its ability to handle complex, high-dimensional data with relatively few training examples. In text classification, for instance, each word can be a dimension, resulting in thousands of features; SVM still finds a separating hyperplane without overfitting. In bioinformatics, SVM helps distinguish disease-related gene expression patterns from healthy ones, guiding diagnostics and drug discovery. Because the model depends only on support vectors, it remains compact and fast to evaluate, which is useful for real-time applications.  \n\nToday, SVM remains a staple in fields where interpretability and reliability matter. Its kernel trick - replacing the dot product with a kernel function - lets practitioners model nonlinear relationships without explicitly computing high-dimensional coordinates. This flexibility makes SVM competitive with deep neural networks on smaller datasets, where deep models would require far more data to generalize. Consequently, industries ranging from finance to autonomous vehicles still rely on SVM for fraud detection, image recognition, and sensor fusion, proving that the method continues to be relevant despite newer techniques.",
