    definition: "Random Forest is an ensemble learning method that builds a collection, or \"forest,\" of decision trees to make predictions for classification or regression tasks. Each tree in the forest is trained on a random subset of the training data, and at each split the algorithm considers only a random subset of the available features. By aggregating the outputs of many diverse trees, the model reduces the variance that a single decision tree would have, leading to more stable and accurate results. The technique works well with high-dimensional data, handles both numeric and categorical variables, and can provide an estimate of feature importance. During training, each tree grows until every leaf is pure or a preset depth is reached, which helps capture complex interactions without overfitting.\n\nThink of a random forest like a panel of medical doctors asked to diagnose a patient. Each doctor looks at a different set of test results and medical history, and each forms an opinion based on that limited view. After everyone has given their diagnosis, the final decision is made by taking the majority vote (for classification) or averaging the numeric predictions (for regression). Because each doctor's perspective is slightly different, occasional mistakes made by one are likely to be outvoted by the others, so the group decision is usually more reliable than any single doctor's judgment. If a few doctors misinterpret a test, their errors are diluted by the consensus, just as a single poorly split tree does not dominate the forest's final vote.\n\nIn practice, random forests have become a go-to tool for data scientists because they require relatively little parameter tuning, are robust to noisy or missing data, and can be trained quickly on modern hardware. They are used in credit-risk scoring, fraud detection, medical imaging, recommendation systems, and many other domains where accurate predictions matter. The built-in feature-importance scores help analysts understand which variables drive outcomes, supporting transparent decision-making in regulated industries. As data volumes keep growing, the ability of random forests to scale across multiple cores and to produce strong results without deep expertise makes them a valuable component of today's machine-learning toolbox. Because the algorithm can be parallelized, enterprises run random forests on clusters, reducing training time from hours to minutes and enabling fast scoring of new observations.",
