    term: "Cluster Analysis",
    slug: "cluster-analysis",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Cluster analysis is a set of statistical methods used to organize a collection of items into groups, called clusters, so that members of the same cluster are more similar to each other than to members of other clusters. The technique does not require pre-labeled examples; instead it discovers structure that is hidden in the data by examining distances or other measures of similarity. Common algorithms include k-means, hierarchical clustering, DBSCAN and Gaussian mixture models, each with its own way of defining what counts as \"close enough\" to belong together. The result is a partition of the dataset that can be visualized, evaluated with silhouette scores, or used as input for downstream models.  \n\nThink of a pile of mixed socks after laundry day. If you spread them out on a table and start pairing socks that look the same - same color, pattern, or thickness - you are performing a mental version of cluster analysis. You are not told in advance how many pairs exist; you simply use visual cues to group items that match. In the same way, a computer examines numeric or categorical features of data points and groups those that share the strongest common traits, while keeping dissimilar points in separate piles.  \n\nCluster analysis matters because it turns raw, unorganized data into actionable insight. In marketing, companies use it to segment customers based on purchase behavior, allowing targeted promotions that increase response rates. In genetics, researchers group gene expression profiles to identify disease subtypes, which can guide personalized treatment plans. In finance, clustering helps detect groups of assets that move together, informing portfolio diversification strategies.  \n\nBeyond these fields, clustering underpins many modern data-driven applications. Recommendation engines rely on clusters of user preferences to suggest movies or products. Urban planners analyze clusters of traffic incidents to prioritize safety improvements. Cybersecurity tools apply clustering to network logs to spot abnormal activity that may signal an intrusion. As data volumes continue to grow, the ability to automatically discover meaningful groupings without supervision remains essential to effective decision-making. These capabilities let organizations respond faster, allocate resources more efficiently, and stay competitive in markets shaped by rapid digital change.",
