    term: "Word Embeddings",
    slug: "word-embeddings",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Word embeddings are numeric representations of words that capture their meanings and relationships in a continuous vector space. Instead of treating each word as an isolated symbol, embeddings map every token to a list of real-valued numbers, typically ranging from 50 to 300 dimensions. In this space, words that appear in similar contexts end up close to each other, while unrelated words are farther apart. The vectors are learned from large text corpora, so they reflect statistical patterns of language without any hand-crafted rules.\n\nThink of a word embedding like a GPS coordinate for a word. Imagine a city map where each address is a point defined by latitude and longitude. If you place \"king\", \"queen\", \"man\", and \"woman\" on that map, the distance and direction between the points will mirror their semantic connections - moving from \"king\" toward \"woman\" and then a similar step brings you to \"queen\". The map is built automatically: every time the algorithm reads a sentence, it nudges the points a little, pulling together words that co-occur and pushing apart those that rarely meet. Over millions of sentences, the map stabilizes and the coordinates become a useful shorthand for meaning.\n\nWord embeddings matter because they turn messy text into a form that computers can process with linear algebra. Machine-learning models that work with vectors can perform classification, translation, sentiment analysis, and question answering far more efficiently than models that manipulate raw strings. By providing a shared numeric language, embeddings allow a single model trained on one dataset to understand new words or domains with minimal extra training.\n\nIn practice, embeddings power everyday applications such as search engines that rank results based on semantic similarity, voice assistants that interpret user intent, and recommendation systems that match products to user reviews. Open-source libraries like GloVe, fastText, and BERT produce embeddings that are reused across research and industry, shrinking development time and improving accuracy. As more textual data becomes available, embeddings continue to serve as the backbone for any system that needs to reason about language.",
