    definition: "Algorithmic bias refers to systematic and repeatable errors in a computer-based decision-making process that produce unfair outcomes for certain groups of people. The bias can appear in any step of the pipeline: data collection, feature selection, model training, or deployment. When an algorithm consistently favors one demographic over another, the result is not a random mistake but a pattern that reflects hidden assumptions, historical inequities, or technical shortcuts. The term is used across fields such as finance, healthcare, hiring, and law enforcement to flag when a machine-driven tool reproduces or amplifies social prejudice.\n\nThink of an algorithm like a kitchen recipe that tells a robot chef how to prepare a dish. If the recipe lists \"use two cups of sugar\" but the pantry only contains brown sugar, and the chef assumes brown sugar tastes the same as white, the final cake will be different for people who prefer a certain flavor. In the same way, an algorithm receives instructions from the data it is fed. If the data over-represent one group or encode past discriminatory decisions, the algorithm will \"cook\" results that reflect those imbalances, even though the code itself never intended to be unfair.\n\nThis matters because many high-stakes decisions now rely on automated scores: loan approvals, medical diagnoses, job shortlists, and parole recommendations. When bias slips into those scores, it can deny credit to qualified borrowers, misclassify patients, exclude capable candidates, or keep people in prison longer than warranted. The impact is not limited to isolated incidents; it can reinforce systemic inequality, erode public trust, and create legal exposure for organizations that deploy the technology.\n\nAddressing algorithmic bias requires a combination of better data practices, transparent model design, and regular performance audits across diverse subpopulations. Developers must ask whether their training set reflects the real world they aim to serve, and whether the metrics they optimize capture fairness as well as accuracy. Policymakers are beginning to draft standards that obligate companies to disclose bias assessments before release. In short, understanding and mitigating algorithmic bias is essential for any system that claims to make decisions on behalf of people, because the fairness of those decisions determines how technology shapes society.",
