    definition: "Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) are collections of autonomous software entities, called agents, that interact within a shared environment to achieve individual or collective goals. Each agent possesses its own perception, decision-making logic, and ability to act, but it does not operate in isolation. The system's overall behavior emerges from the repeated exchanges among these agents, which may cooperate, compete, or negotiate depending on the problem they are designed to solve.\n\nThink of a MAS like a busy kitchen where each chef specializes in a different dish. The head chef (the system designer) supplies a recipe book (the overall objective) but does not dictate every stir or garnish. Each chef watches the stove, tastes the sauce, and decides when to add salt or pass a utensil to a colleague. The final meal's flavor results from these coordinated, on-the-fly adjustments rather than a single cook following a fixed script.\n\nToday, MAS underpin many technologies that require distributed decision making. In traffic management, each vehicle can act as an agent that shares speed and position data, allowing the flow to self-organize and reduce congestion. In smart grids, homes and generators negotiate power usage in real time, balancing supply and demand without a central controller. In financial markets, algorithmic traders act as agents that react to price signals, providing liquidity and enabling rapid price discovery. Robotics swarms use simple agents that follow local rules to explore hazardous sites, map terrain, or perform search-and-rescue tasks.\n\nBecause the overall outcome is not programmed directly, designers must focus on defining clear interaction protocols and incentive structures that guide agents toward desirable states. This approach offers scalability: adding more agents rarely requires redesigning the whole system. It also provides robustness; when some agents fail, the remaining ones can often compensate. As the Internet of Things expands and autonomous vehicles become commonplace, MAS will become a foundational tool for coordinating billions of devices safely and efficiently. Researchers continue to refine learning mechanisms that let agents adapt without human oversight.",
