    term: "Vision Transformers (ViT)",
    slug: "vision-transformers-vit",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Vision Transformers, often abbreviated as ViT, are a class of deep-learning models that adapt the transformer architecture - originally created for natural-language processing - to analyze visual data such as photographs or video frames. Instead of using convolutional layers that slide filters across an image, a ViT first splits the picture into a sequence of fixed-size patches, flattens each patch, and then feeds the resulting token list into a standard transformer encoder. The model learns to recognize patterns by attending to relationships between patches, much like a language model learns word dependencies.  \n\nImagine you have a jigsaw puzzle where each piece shows a small portion of a larger picture. A traditional convolutional network would examine each piece by looking at its immediate neighbors, gradually building a sense of the whole. A Vision Transformer, on the other hand, treats every piece as a word in a sentence. It asks each piece to consider every other piece at the same time, deciding which parts are most relevant for understanding the scene. This \"all-to-all\" attention lets the model capture long-range relationships without being constrained by a fixed receptive field.  \n\nVision Transformers have become popular because they often achieve higher accuracy on large image classification benchmarks while using fewer training epochs than comparable convolutional models. Their ability to process images as sequences makes it easy to combine visual data with text or audio in a single transformer, which simplifies the design of multimodal systems. Companies that need to analyze massive image collections - such as satellite-imagery providers, medical-imaging firms, or e-commerce platforms - can benefit from the scalability and performance that ViT offers.  \n\nIn research labs, ViT serves as a common backbone for tasks beyond classification, including object detection, segmentation, and video understanding. Because the same transformer code can be reused across these tasks, engineers spend less time rewriting architecture-specific layers and more time fine-tuning data. As hardware continues to improve, especially with accelerators optimized for matrix-multiplication, the computational pattern of Vision Transformers aligns well with future processors, suggesting that they will remain a central tool for visual AI for years to come.",
