    term: "Public-Key Cryptography",
    slug: "public-key-cryptography",
    category: "Web3",
    definition: "Public-key cryptography, also known as asymmetric cryptography, secures digital information using two mathematically linked keys - a public key anyone can see and a private key kept secret by its owner. The public key encrypts data or verifies a digital signature; the private key decrypts data or creates a signature. Because the keys are paired, a message encrypted with the public key can be opened only with the matching private key, and a signature made with the private key can be checked by anyone who has the public key. This replaces the older practice of sharing a single secret key among participants.\n\nImagine a mailbox with a slot that anyone can drop a letter into, but only the homeowner has a unique key that opens the back door to retrieve the mail. The slot is the public key - open for anyone to use, yet it does not give access to the contents. The homeowner's private key is the only thing that can unlock the box and read the letters. Likewise, a sender can lock a digital message with the recipient's public key, and only the recipient's private key can unlock it. For digital signatures, the sender locks a hash of the message with their private key, and anyone can verify it with the sender's public key.\n\nIn today's networked world, public-key cryptography underlies secure web browsing, email encryption, and mobile app authentication. When you see \"https\" in a browser address bar, the site's server uses a public key to create an encrypted channel that stops eavesdroppers from reading the traffic. Email programs that support OpenPGP or S/MIME rely on the same math to keep messages private and to prove the sender's identity. Mobile devices exchange short-lived session keys using public-key pairs, protecting data while you shop or bank online.\n\nPublic-key cryptography also powers blockchain platforms, software supply-chain verification, and Internet of Things devices that need strong security with resources. Because the private key never leaves its owner's control, trust can be established between parties that have never met. This ability to authenticate and encrypt without sharing secrets makes e-commerce, cloud services, and work possible at scale. As cyber threats evolve, researchers keep refining the underlying math, but the idea remains the foundation of secure communication on the Internet.",
