    term: "Soft Fork",
    slug: "soft-fork",
    category: "Web3",
    definition: "Soft fork is a method of changing the rules that govern a blockchain without requiring every participant to upgrade their software at the same time. In a soft fork the new rules are a subset of the old ones, meaning that blocks created under the new rules are still considered valid by nodes that continue to run the previous version. This backward-compatible approach lets the network evolve while keeping the majority of existing infrastructure functional.\n\nThink of a soft fork like a house renovation that adds a new type of door while keeping the old door frames intact. The builders install the new door, which fits into the same opening as the original. Anyone who still uses the old door can open and close the house without noticing a problem, because the opening hasn't changed. The new door, however, offers extra security features that only the renovated rooms can use. In the same way, a soft fork adds stricter validation rules that older nodes can still recognize as acceptable.\n\nSoft forks matter because they let a blockchain adopt improvements - such as faster transaction processing, reduced data size, or stronger cryptographic checks - without forcing every participant to halt operations and install new software. Since older nodes continue to accept the newer blocks, the network can transition smoothly, avoiding the disruption that a hard fork would cause. This flexibility reduces the risk of a split, where two incompatible chains might emerge, and helps maintain a single, unified ledger.\n\nToday several major blockchains have used soft forks to roll out features that users rely on daily. Bitcoin introduced the SegWit upgrade, which changed how transaction signatures are stored and freed up block space, allowing more payments per block without breaking older wallets. Ethereum applied the London upgrade, adding a fee-burn mechanism that altered gas pricing while keeping legacy clients operational. For developers, a soft fork means they can write code that takes advantage of new rules without abandoning users on older versions, and for end users it usually appears as a seamless, invisible improvement.",
