    definition: "Peer-to-Peer (P2P) describes a network architecture in which each computer, device, or node can act both as a client and as a server, sharing resources directly with other participants without needing a central coordinating server. In a P2P system, every participant holds equal status, can initiate requests, and can provide data, processing power, storage, or other services to the network. This contrasts with the classic client-server model where a small number of dedicated servers supply all resources to many clients.\n\nImagine a group of friends sitting around a table, each with a stack of postcards they are willing to exchange. Instead of one friend acting as a mailroom that collects all postcards and redistributes them, each person can hand a postcard directly to another who needs it. The exchange happens through mutual agreements, and the whole group can continue trading as long as at least two people are present. In a P2P network, the \"friends\" are computers, the \"postcards\" are files or processing tasks, and the table represents the shared communication medium.\n\nThe importance of P2P lies in its ability to distribute load across many machines, which reduces bottlenecks and improves resilience. When a file is split into many pieces and stored on multiple peers, a single point of failure disappears; if one node goes offline, the remaining nodes can still supply the missing parts. This property makes P2P attractive for large-scale content distribution, software updates, and decentralized services that need to stay online even under heavy traffic or partial network outages.\n\nToday, P2P underpins popular applications such as file-sharing platforms, blockchain networks, and real-time collaboration tools. By using the collective bandwidth and storage of participants, these services can scale without massive investment in centralized infrastructure. Additionally, P2P enables privacy-focused communication, because data can travel through many independent routes rather than passing through a single overseer. As internet usage continues to grow, the P2P model provides a flexible, cost-effective way to handle massive data flows while keeping the network robust against failures and censorship.",
