    term: "Hot Wallet",
    slug: "hot-wallet",
    category: "Web3",
    definition: "A hot wallet is a type of cryptocurrency storage that is connected to the internet at all times. It holds the private keys needed to sign transactions for digital assets such as Bitcoin, Ethereum, or stablecoins. Because the keys are stored in a software environment that can be accessed online, users can send and receive funds instantly from a desktop computer, mobile phone, or web interface. Hot wallets come in many forms, including desktop applications, mobile apps, browser extensions, and online services offered by exchanges. Their primary advantage is convenience; the trade-off is that an internet-connected device is always exposed to potential hacking attempts, malware, or phishing attacks.\n\nThink of a hot wallet like a debit card linked to a checking account that you carry in your pocket. Just as the card lets you swipe at a store and the bank instantly moves money, the hot wallet lets you tap a QR code or copy an address and the blockchain immediately records the transfer. The card and the checking account are both online-connected; the bank can see the balance and authorize the spend in real time. If you lose the card or someone steals your PIN, they can withdraw funds until you block it. The same risk exists for a hot wallet: anyone who gains access to the device or the password can move the stored crypto without further permission.\n\nHot wallets matter because they enable everyday transactions in the crypto economy. Without a fast, internet-ready tool, users would have to rely on cold storage solutions - hardware devices or paper backups - that require extra steps before any money can move. Those extra steps add friction and slow down merchants, traders, and developers who need to react to price changes or settle payments within seconds. By keeping a portion of funds online, individuals can participate in decentralized finance protocols, pay for services, or receive salaries in digital form with the same ease as a traditional online bank account.",
