    term: "Proof of History (PoH)",
    slug: "proof-of-history-poh",
    category: "Web3",
    definition: "Proof of History (PoH) is a cryptographic clock that creates a verifiable sequence of events without requiring participants to constantly agree on the current time. In a PoH-based system, each event is hashed together with the hash of the previous event, forming a chain of data that anyone can check for integrity. The result is a timestamped record that proves a particular piece of information existed at a specific point in the ordered sequence. PoH does not replace consensus mechanisms like Proof of Stake; instead, it supplies an immutable ordering that other protocols can reference when they need to know the exact order of transactions.\n\nThink of PoH as a notebook where each page includes the fingerprint of the previous page before you write anything new. When you turn to a page, the fingerprint proves that every earlier page was already there and unchanged. In the same way, PoH takes the hash of the last entry, mixes it with new data, and records the result as the next entry. Anyone looking at the notebook can verify the order simply by re-hashing each page and confirming the chain matches. This process requires only a single node to perform the hashing, so the time stamp is created quickly and can be shared with the whole network.\n\nBecause PoH supplies a trusted ordering, blockchain platforms that adopt it can process many more transactions per second than traditional designs that wait for every node to agree on time. The fast, verifiable sequence lets validators focus on confirming that the data itself is correct, rather than spending resources on building the timeline. This efficiency translates into lower fees for users, smoother performance for decentralized apps, and the ability to handle workloads similar to those of centralized services. As more enterprises experiment with public-or private ledgers for supply-chain tracking, financial settlement, or IoT data streams, the guarantee of an immutable chronological record becomes a key factor in meeting regulatory and audit requirements.",
