    term: "Web2",
    slug: "web2",
    category: "Tech",
    definition: "Web2, often written as Web 2.0, describes the second generation of the World Wide Web that emerged in the early 2000s. Unlike the static pages of the original web, Web2 emphasizes interactive, user-generated content, social networking, and cloud-based services. In this model, websites act as platforms where people can not only read information but also create, share, and remix it in real time. The shift from a read-only environment to a read-write-participate model is the core characteristic that defines Web2.  \n\nThink of Web2 as a community garden instead of a traditional park. In a park, visitors walk by, admire the scenery, and maybe sit on a bench, but they never change the layout. In a community garden, each person brings seeds, plants a plot, waters the beds, and harvests together. The garden thrives because every participant adds something new, and the overall space evolves with each contribution. Web2 works the same way: users supply the content, platforms provide the tools, and the whole digital space grows dynamically.  \n\nWeb2 matters because it turned the internet into a global marketplace for ideas and services. Social media platforms let businesses reach customers without a traditional storefront, while crowd-sourced projects like Wikipedia provide free reference material to anyone with a connection. The ability to post a video, launch a crowdfunding campaign, or share a software update instantly reshapes how products are discovered, funded, and improved. This openness also creates new career paths, such as influencer marketing, community management, and platform engineering.  \n\nIn everyday life, the Web2 model influences how people stay informed, socialize, and solve problems. News feeds aggregate stories from dozens of sources, giving readers a personalized snapshot of current events. Messaging apps replace phone calls for many families, lowering cost and expanding reach. Open-source communities collaborate on software that powers everything from smartphones to spacecraft, proving that distributed contribution can produce reliable, high-quality results. As these patterns become embedded in culture, they shape expectations for transparency, speed, and participation in both public and private sectors.",
