    term: "Spatial Computing",
    slug: "spatial-computing",
    category: "Tech",
    definition: "Spatial computing is a set of technologies that lets digital information exist and interact within three-dimensional space, as if it were a physical object you could see, touch, or move. It blends sensors, computer vision, graphics, and real-time processing to map the geometry of an environment and then overlay data onto that map. The result is a hybrid view where the virtual and the physical coexist, enabling devices to understand where you are, what you are looking at, and how you might act on that information.\n\nImagine you are standing in a room with a transparent sheet of paper that automatically draws a sketch of everything around you. As you walk, the paper updates the drawing, adding furniture, windows, and people in the right places. When you point at a chair, a label appears on the sheet showing its size, material, or price. That sheet is a simple picture of what spatial computing does: it continuously captures the real world, creates a digital replica, and lets software attach useful data to any point in that replica.\n\nToday, spatial computing powers many applications that people use every day. In retail, smartphones can scan a store aisle and instantly show product reviews, stock levels, or virtual try-on options. In construction, helmets equipped with depth sensors project wiring diagrams onto walls, reducing errors and speeding up installation. In education, classrooms can turn any surface into an interactive whiteboard, letting students manipulate 3-D models of molecules or historical artifacts without needing separate hardware. These examples show how the technology turns abstract data into something you can see and act on in the moment.\n\nThe broader impact of spatial computing lies in how it changes the way humans and machines collaborate. By giving computers a sense of space, designers can prototype products in a virtual environment before any physical part exists, cutting material waste. City planners can simulate traffic flow or emergency response on a digital twin of the downtown area, testing scenarios that would be too costly to try in reality. As sensors become cheaper and processing power grows, the line between the digital overlay and the physical world will keep thinning, making context-aware experiences a normal part of daily life.",
